<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>PART NAME</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 28.35pt 3pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:none">The Law Commission</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:none"> for England and Wales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:none"> – Supplementary written evidence</span></h1><h1 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 28.35pt 3pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">ANSWERS TO FURTHER QUESTIONS FROM THE COM</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">MITTEE ON THE DEREGULATION BILL</span></h1><h2 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 28.35pt 3pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">(a) Lord Justice </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Lloyd </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Jones said the Law Commission invited departments to submit candidates for repeal in June 2011. Was this the only opportunity that Departments had to provide suggestions to the Law Commission since the Red Tape Challenge which we</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> understood started in May 2011?</span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-29.49pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">June 2011 was when the Commission wrote to Departments inviting them to submit candidates for the next cycle of SLR work starting in 2012. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There has been no further request made since then. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Departments </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> however, free to submit candidates at any time. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Indeed the S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tatute Law (Repeals)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Act 2013 contained a number of repeals submitted by Departments and others after the work leading up to that Act had started. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In other words</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> there is a rolling programme of SLR work carried out at the Commission</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> which Departments and others can contribute to at any time. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Obviously</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> if it is left too late in the run up to a Bill</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> it will be impossible to process it in time for that Bill and instead it would be picked up as part of our next cycle of work.</span></p><h2 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 28.35pt 3pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">(b) Has the Law Commission received suggestions for repeals from the Better Regulation Executive since 2010?</span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-29.49pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are not aware that the Better Regulation Executive has ever sent the Commis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ion any suggestions for repealing obsolete legislation.</span></p><h2 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 28.35pt 3pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">(c) Lord Justice </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Lloyd Jones</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> said your research suggests the Law Commission has rarely been consulted in relation to Legislative Reform Orders. Would you be able to share that research with us so we can see how many suggestions were taken forward, if any?</span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-29.49pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our research shows that 20 Legislative Reform Orders have been made pursuant to the Legislative and Regulatory Reform Act 2006. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">With three exceptions we have found no evidence that the Commission was consulted on any of them. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The exceptions are the Legislative Reform (Limited Partnerships) Order 2009 (which implemented a Law Commission proposal and so involved input from the Commission), the Legislative Reform (Health and Safety Executive) Order 2008 and the Legislative Reform (Local Government) (Animal Health Functions) Order 2009.  The Commission did not respond to the latter two consultations. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-29.49pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our research also examined the position under the Regulatory Reform Act 2001, which was superseded by the 2006 Act. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Of the 30 Regulatory Reform Orders made under the 2001 Act, the only evidence that we have found that the Commission was consulted on any of them relates to two orders that implemented Law Commission proposals. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In conducting our research we used information provided by the LexisNexis website.</span></p><h2 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 28.35pt 3pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">d) T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">he Law Commission is independent from Government and its functions contained in statute. Has the Government reviewed those functions, in particular “the repeal of obsolete and unnecessary enactments” by the Statute Law Repeals Team and what were the recommendations in relation to the three tests e.g. external expertise,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> impartiality and independence? </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">(I draw upon the Triennial Review here - </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/226315/law-commission-triennial-review-stage-1.PDF"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/226315/law-commission-triennial-review-stage-1.PDF</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">)</span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-29.49pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Law Commission has been reviewed a number of times over the years. Each time it has been reviewed all of its functions have been retained. The most recent review is a Triennial Review. Stage 1 of the review has been completed and the outcome reported to Parliament (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">which you have referred in your footnote)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The characteristics enjoyed by the Commission in terms of its independence, impartiality and expertise apply to its SLR function as they do to the Commission</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> more general law reform functions.  Respondents to the Triennial Review who commented on the Commission’s SLR function were overwhelmingly in support of this area of the Commission’s work. The following is an extract from the report by the Ministry of Justice on Stage 1 in relation to the Statute Law Repeal function</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">paras</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 50-52):</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 56.7pt 12pt 85.05pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This function has an important role in reducing regulation and red tape, helping to remove unnecessary law and making the statute book more accessible for individuals and businesses applying it. For example, as noted above, the most recent Statute Law (Repeals) Bill included tax law provisions from 2010 that had been overtaken by subsequent changes but were still technically in force and therefore a potential source of confusion. This function of removing obsolete and unnecessary legislation complements the Government’s Red Tape Challenge process, which aims to identify and remove legislation that, while still in active use, is deemed unnecessary and unhelpful.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 56.7pt 12pt 85.05pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There was some limited discussion of the value of the repeals function among a few respondents to the call for evidence. This minority felt that the function was not perhaps the best use of limited resources, as obsolete law has no practical effect and therefore does no harm. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 56.7pt 12pt 85.05pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, as with other functions, most respondents were in favour of its retention. This was not only based on the principle of rule of law and the benefits of an accessible statute book but also reflected the fact that the function remains in regular use, an argument borne out by the function’s links to Government priorities. As the volume of statute law passed in 2009 alone stood at 23 Acts and 2247 pages,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:4pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the need for repeal is likely to remain in future.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-29.49pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In relation to the Law Commission’s functions as a whole the report concluded</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">para</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 55)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 56.7pt 12pt 85.05pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The overwhelming weight of evidence from respondents to the call for evidence is in favour of retaining all of the Commission’s substantive functions. The Government agrees with this conclusion, in view of the clear contribution these functions make to the development of better and more effective law.</span></p><h2 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 28.35pt 3pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">(e) Lord Sharkey asked about the time scale it would take to review the clauses in the draft Bill to determine how long it would take the Law Commission. The Draft Bill contains many examples of this not just in Schedule 16. If those were identified to you, Lord Sharkey was interested in ascertaining how long this would have taken. The discussion later suggested this would have been a standard part of an SLR </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">workstream</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> which may take up to six months if specifically prioritised. Would this be a fair estimate?</span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-29.49pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is important to grasp that the SLR work carried out by the Commission relates solely to the repeal of laws that are obsolete or otherwise no longer of practical utility. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For that reason, the Commission's evidence on the draft Deregulation Bill relates solely to the provisions in the Bill (clauses 50 to 57 and Schedule 16) that are concerned with the repeal of laws of this kind. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Most of the Bill appears to relate to the freeing of businesses and individuals from "red tape" and unnecessary burdens. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">That amounts to the repeal of laws that are actually having an effect whereas the Commission's SLR work is concerned with the repeal of laws that have no effect even though they remain in force as a matter of law.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-29.49pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As to how long it might take the Commission to run a project to repeal the sort of obsolete laws that appear in Schedule 16, our SLR Bills typically contain around 10 topics or projects and we estimate that these take between 4 and 12 months to complete, depending on the size and complexity of the topic.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A topic can cover very many individual pieces of legislation. For example, the tax legislation topic in the Statute Law </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Repeals</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Act 2013</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">repealed 56 Acts in whole or part. The railways topic in the same Act repealed 297 Acts</span></p><h2 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 28.35pt 3pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">(e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1) Lord Justice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Lloyd</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Jones mentioned there </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">was</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> a minimum number of steps which needed to be done for any exercise of repeals. Would you mind setting these out for committee staff in order to compare against the process the Government is proposing?</span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-29.49pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.9</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Each SLR project starts with research, moves onto consultation on the research, and finishes in the form of a report and draft Bill to the Justice Secretary. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The research tests each repeal candidate (there may be well over a hundred in any repeals project) to check whether it is of any practical utility. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This will include checking Parliamentary records including the original debates on the candidate, examining other public records, and studying a range of legal and historical works to provide context and background information. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The research is then written up and issued as a consultation paper to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> persons</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in central or local government, in industry or elsewhere who may be in a position to examine and comment on the repeal proposals. Typically we will consult for up to 3 months, dealing with enquiries and responses during that time. After the consultation period has closed we move into producing the draft Bill and report which is sent to the Justice Secretary for introduction into the legislative process. The Law Commission’s written evidence provides more information on the special legislative procedure that applies to its Statute Law </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Repeals</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Bills.</span></p><h2 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 28.35pt 3pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">(f) Lord Naseby picked up in Q77 about the Law Commission procedures but Lord Justice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Lloyd</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Jones responded that the Law Commission has suggested a number of proposals upon how the procedures could be improved. Would you mind drawing my attention to some of the latest suggestions by the Statute Law Repeals Team if they are published or in annual reports?</span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.10</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The proposals referred to are those set out in the Law Commission's evidence to the Committee in paragraphs 37 to 41. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">They relate to (1) improved communications between Government and the Commission</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (2) the possibility of more frequent SLR Bills</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (3) using SLR Bills to revoke secondary legislation where this is appropriate.</span></p><h2 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 28.35pt 3pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">(g) John Hemming MP was keen to ask whether you had been on the repeal of the Grey Squirrels (Prohibition of Importation and Keeping) Order 1937 (S.I. 1937/478). Have any of the measures under Schedule 11 of the Draft Deregulation Bill been brought to your attention by the departments?</span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.11</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To the best of our knowledge, Departments have not asked us to consider the revocation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of the Grey Squirrels (Prohibition of Importation and Keeping) Order 1937.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> However, both that order and the Destructive Imported Animals Act 1932 are under review as part of the Commission's Wildlife law reform project.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Commission is not concerned with any other provision in Schedule 11 to the Bill.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 28.35pt 3pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">(h)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Chairman in Q82/Q92 was drawing attention to the awareness in Parliament of the Law Commission and its work. Has there been any engagement such as training or events that the Law Commission or its Commissioners has had with the House of Commons or All-Party Parliamentary Groups since 2010? </span></h2><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.12</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Since 2010 the Law Commission has engaged with Members of the House of Commons on a number of levels. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.13</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In June 2010 the Chairman, Law Commissioners and Chief Executive were present at an event held in the Foreign and Commonwealth Office to welcome the new intake of MPs to Parliament. We have since hosted a consultation event of our own in Parliament in October 2013, to which we invited over 100 Parliamentarians.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.14</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have twice staged exhibitions in the Houses of Parliament (February 2011, October 201</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, providing opportunities for MPs and Peers to find out about the work we do and meet the Chairman, Commissioners and Chief Executive of the Commission.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.15</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Law Commissioners have given evidence at a number of Select and Special Public Bill Committees:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 96.4pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-31.89pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(1)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2010 January: Special Public Bill Committee, Third Party (Rights against Insurers) Bill</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 96.4pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-31.89pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(2)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2011 November: Health Select Committee, Adult Social Care</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 96.4pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-31.89pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(3)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2011 October: Special Public Bill Committee, Consumer Insurance (Disclosure and Representations) Bill</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 96.4pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-31.89pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(4)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2011 November: Justice Select Committee, Joint </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Enterprise</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 96.4pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-31.89pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(5)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2012 November: Special Public Bill Committee, Trusts (Capital and Income) Bill</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 96.4pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-31.89pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(6)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2012 December: Consolidation Bills Joint Committee, Statute Law (Repeals) Bill</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 96.4pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-31.89pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(7)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2013 October: Political and Constitutional Reform Committee, inquiry into ensuring the standards in the quality of legislation</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 96.4pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-31.89pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(8)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2013 January: Joint Committee on Draft Care and Support Bill </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 96.4pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-31.89pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(9)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2013 October: BIS Select Committee, Consumer Rights Bill</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 96.4pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-38.01pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(10)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2013 October: Joint Committee, Draft Deregulation Bill</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 96.4pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-38.01pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(11)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2013 October: Transport Select Committee, Level Crossings Report</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 77.95pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.16</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our engagement with All Party Parliamentary Groups has included meetings with the APPGs for Insurance and Financial Services, and for Consumer Affairs.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.17</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Commissioners engage with Ministers responsible for the policy areas within which our projects fall. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.18</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have also had contact with Parliamentarians taking forward our recommendations in Private Members Bills, notably The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Rt</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Hon Sir Greg Knight MP regarding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Estates of Deceased Persons (Forfeiture Rule and Law of Succession) Act</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 2011</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> In May 2010, September 2012 and October 2013, we wrote to the Ministers whose new portfolios included areas of law under review by the Law Commission. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.19</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In summer 2010 the Chairman invited all Parliamentarians to take part in the consultation for our 11th Programme of law reform. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.20</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Other engagement takes place on an individual level. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.21</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Members of Parliament were invited to the Leslie </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Scarman</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Lecture in January 2012 and to a stakeholder event we held in November 2011. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.22</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Chairman and Commissioners attend various events at which Parliamentarians are represented, for example, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">annual</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">British Insurance Brokers parliamentary reception, which members of the IFS APPG attend together with Treasury Ministers.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.23</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We also have an ongoing presence on </span><a href="http://www.politicshome.com"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">www.politicshome.com</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, the “most read, commercial, political news website in Parliament”.</span></p><h2 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 28.35pt 3pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">) Has the Law Commission been involved since 2010 in the reform of law in relation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> to Land Use in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Wales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">?</span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.24</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The projects most directly concerned with land use in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and Wales that the Commission has been involved in since 2010 are the following.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 96.4pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-31.89pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(1)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Easements, covenants and profits a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">prendre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The Law Commission published its report on 8</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> June 2011 and is waiting for the Government’s response.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 96.4pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-31.89pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(2)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Electronic Communications Code. The Law Commission published its report on 28</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> February 2013 and is waiting for the Government’s response.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 96.4pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-31.89pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(3)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Rights to light. This is a current project. We expect to report by the end of 2014.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 96.4pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-31.89pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(4)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Conservation covenants. This is a current project. We expect to report by the end of May 2014.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.25</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Further details on all these projects can be found on the Law Commission’s website.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (</span><a href="http://lawcommission.justice.gov.uk/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">lawcommission.justice.gov.uk</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">).</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:11pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">              </span></p></div></body></html>